This requires the fraction \[ \frac{\log (n^2) - (\log n)^2}{\log n - 3} \] to be non-negative. First, we simplify the numerator and denominator. The numerator is \( \log(n^2) - (\log n)^2 = 2 \log |n| - (\log |n|)^2 \). Letting \( x = \log |n| \), the numerator becomes \( x(2 - x) \). The denominator is \( \log n - 3 \). Since \( n \) must be a positive integer (as the logarithm of a negative number is undefined), we consider \( \log n \) for positive integers \( n \). We analyze the inequality: \[ \frac{x(2 - x)}{x - 3} \geq 0 \] where \( x = \log n \). The critical points are \( x = 0 \), \( x = 2 \), and \( x = 3 \). Testing intervals around these points, we find the solution set is \( x \in (-\infty, 0] \cup (2, 3) \). Converting back to \( n \): 1. \( x \leq 0 \) corresponds to \( n = 1 \) (since \( \log 1 = 0 \)). 2. \( 2 < x < 3 \) corresponds to \( 100 < n < 1000 \), which includes integers from 101 to 999.
